      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements with an avionics equipment manufacturer and maintenance provider that
has a guaranteed minimum annual flight hour requirement. The minimum guaranteed
amount based on the Company's current operations is </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$4.9 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> per year through December&#160;2014 for
the ERJ-145 family of aircraft and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$8.2 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> per year through December 2014 for the
ERJ-170 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">family of
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aircraft. The Company did
not record a liability for this guarantee because the Company does not believe
that any aircraft will be utilized below the minimum flight hour requirement
during the term of the agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements with </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aviation
equipment manufacturers </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">to
maintain the auxiliary power units </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">for the ERJ-145 family of aircraft and
the CRJ-200 regional aircraft through </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">June 2013 and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> December 2012, respectively. The
agreement has a penalty payment provision if more than twenty percent of the
Company's aircraft are removed from service based on the annual flight activity
prior to the date of removal. The Company did not record a liability for this
penalty provision because the Company does not believe that more than twenty
percent of their aircraft will be removed from service during the term of the
agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements based upon </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">flight activity with engine
manufacturers through</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">February 2010 for the
CRJ-200 aircraft, October </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2012 for the ERJ-145 family</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> of aircraft</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> and through December 2014 for the
ERJ-170 family of aircraft.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements for </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">wheels and
brakes through</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
June&#160;2014 for the ERJ-145 family of aircraft and through </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">February </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2017 for the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ERJ</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">170 family of aircraft</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The agreement has an early termination
penalty, if the Company removes seller's equipment from certain aircraft, sells
or leases certain aircraft to a third party or terminates the services prior to
expiration of the agreement. The Company did not record a liability for this
penalty provision, because the Company does not believe the contract will be
terminated prior to the expiration date.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has a long-term agreement to
provide, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">manage and repair
certain airframe components and spare parts on</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> the CRJ-200 aircraft through December
2009.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Total payments under these long-term
maintenance agreements were $</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">76.8 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $56.1 million and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">53.6 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> for the years ended December&#160;31,
200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">7</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, 2006 and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> 200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">5</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">,
respectively.&#160;</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Our commercial commitments at December
31, 2007 include letters of credit totaling </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$12.5 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;expiring within one
year.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Cash payments for interest were
approximately </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$105.8
million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> in 2007. Tax
payments in 2007 were not significant and we are not expecting significant
payments in 2008.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">

        <div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-44-</font></div>
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center">

        <div id="HDR">
          <div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Critical Accounting
Policies</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The discussion and analysis of our
financial condition and results of operations are based upon the consolidated
financial statements, which have been prepared in accordance with accounting
principles generally accepted in the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">United States</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The preparation of these financial
statements requires us to make estimates and judgments that affect the reported
amount of assets and liabilities, revenues and expenses, and related disclosure
of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of our financial statements.
Actual results may differ from these estimates under different assumptions and
conditions.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Critical accounting policies are defined
as those that are reflective of significant judgments and uncertainties, and are
sufficiently sensitive to result in materially different results under different
assumptions and conditions. We believe that our critical accounting policies are
limited to those described below. For a detailed discussion on the application
of these and other accounting policies, see Note&#160;2 in the notes to the
consolidated financial statements.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Revenue
Recognition</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. Under our fixed-fee
arrangements with American, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">Delta</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">US</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">Airways, United,
Continental and Frontier, the Company receives a fixed-fee, as well as
reimbursement of specified costs on a gross basis with additional possible
incentives from our Partners for superior service. Revenues are recognized in
the period the service is provided, and we perform an estimate of the profit
component based upon the information available at the end of the accounting
period. The reimbursement of specified costs, known as &#8220;pass-through costs&#8221;, may
include aircraft ownership cost, passenger liability and hull insurance,
aircraft property taxes, fuel, landing fees and catering. All revenue recognized
under these contracts is presented at the gross amount billed for reimbursement
pursuant to Emerging Issues Tax Force Issue (&#8220;E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">F&#8221;) No. 99-19&#160;
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Reporting
Revenue Gross as a Principal versus Net as an Agent</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Under the Company&#8217;s code-share
agreements, the Company is reimbursed an amount per aircraft designed to
compensate the Company for certain aircraft ownership costs. In accordance with
E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">F No.&#160;01-08, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Determining Whether
an Arrangement Contains a Lease</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, the Company has concluded that a
component of its revenue under the agreement discussed above is rental income,
inasmuch as the agreement identifies the &#8220;right of use&#8221; of a specific type and
number of aircraft over a stated period of time. The amount deemed to be rental
income during fiscal 2007, 2006 and 2005 was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$310.3 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $258.6&#160;million and
$189.8&#160;million, respectively, and has been included in regional airline
services revenue on the Company&#8217;s consolidated statements of
income.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Aircraft
Leases</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">.
The Company has aircraft that are leased from third parties. In order to
determine the proper classification of a lease as either an operating lease or a
capital lease, the Company must make certain estimates at the inception of the
lease relating to the economic useful life and the fair value of an asset as
well as select an appropriate discount rate to be used in discounting future
lease payments. These estimates are utilized by management in making
computations as required by existing accounting standards that determine whether
the lease is classified as an operating lease or a capital lease. All of the
Company&#8217;s aircraft leases have been classified as operating leases, which
results in rental payments being charged to expense over the term of the related
leases. Additionally, operating leases are not reflected in the Company&#8217;s
consolidated balance sheet and accordingly, neither a lease asset nor an
obligation for future lease payments is reflected in the Company&#8217;s consolidated
balance sheet. The Company is responsible for all other maintenance costs of its
aircraft and must meet specified return conditions upon lease expiration for
both the airframes and engines. The Company is unable to estimate the liability
for these return conditions as of December 31, 2007, because the leases expire
beginning in 2009. The Company will record a liability for these return
conditions once the liability is probable and reasonably
estimable.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Impairments
to Long-Lived Assets</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. We record impairment
losses on long-lived assets used in operations when events and circumstances
indicate that the assets might be impaired and the undiscounted cash flows
estimated to be generated by those assets are less than the carrying amount of
those items. Our cash flow estimates are based on historical results adjusted to
reflect our best estimate of future market and operating conditions. Our
estimates of fair value represent our best estimate based on industry trends and
reference to market rates and transactions. We review, at least annually, the
estimated useful lives and salvage values for our owned aircraft and spare
parts.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Aircraft
Maintenance and Repair</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. We follow a method of
expensing aircraft maintenance and repair costs as</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000"> incurred</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. However, maintenance
and repairs for engines and airframe components under power-by-the-hour
contracts, such as engines, avionics, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">AP</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">Us, wheels and brakes,
are expensed as the aircraft are operated based upon actual hours or cycles
flown.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Issued
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Warrants</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. Warrants issued to
non-employees are accounted for under SFAS No.&#160;123(R), </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Share-Based
Payments,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">and E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">F&#160;96-18,
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting
for Equity Instruments That Are Issued to Other Than Employees for Acquiring, or
in Conjunction with Selling, Goods or Services</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">, at fair value on the
measurement date. Fair value for warrants issued to Delta, for which a
measurement date has occurred, have been determined based upon the estimated
fair value of the equity instrument issued rather than the consideration
received because we believe it is more reliably measured. Various option pricing
models are available; however, we have used a model that allows continuous
compounding of dividends which begins three years after the grant date and the
dilutive effects of our initial public offering and the follow-on offerings in
2005. Option pricing models require estimates of dividend yield, a risk free
rate commensurate with the warrant term, stock volatility and the expected life
of the warrant. Each of these variables has been determined based upon relevant
industry market data, our strategic business plan and consultation with
appropriate professionals experienced in valuing similar equity
instruments.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
        <div id="FTR">
          <div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-45-</font></div>

            <hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="HDR">
          <div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Deferred
gain - Delta Pre-Petition Claim and Surrendered </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Warrants</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">.&#160;&#160;<font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">As a result of the
Delta amendment, in March 2007, we recorded a deferred credit of $44,590, which
represented the net realizable value of the pre-petition claim on the approval
date by the Bankruptcy Court. In addition, we recorded a deferred gain on the
surrender of the warrants from Delta of $42,735, which was net of the write-off
of the previously reported unamortized deferred warrant charge of $6,369. The
deferred credits for the proceeds of the pre-petition claim and the gain on the
surrender of the warrants totaling $87,325 will be amortized as an adjustment to
revenue over&#160;the weighted average aircraft in service during the term of
the agreements with Delta. </font></font></font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Income
Taxes</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. The
Company has generated significant net operating losses (&#8220;NOLs&#8221;) for federal
income tax purposes primarily from accelerated depreciation on owned aircraft.
In July 2005, Wexford Capital LLC&#8217;s ownership percentage of the Company was
reduced to less than 50% as a result of a follow-on offering of our common
stock. As a result of this decrease in ownership, the utilization of NOLs
generated prior to July 2005 are subject to an annual limitation under Internal
Revenue Code Section 382 (&#8220;IRC 382&#8221;). The annual limitation is based upon the
enterprise value of the Company on the IRC 382 ownership change date multiplied
by the applicable long-term tax exempt rate. If the utilization of pre July 2005
NOLs becomes uncertain in future years, we will be required to record a
valuation allowance for the NOLs not expected to be
utilized.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Intangible
Commuter Slots</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">. The Company acquired
commuter slots during 2005 at the New York-LaGuardia and Ronald Reagan
Washington National airports from US Airways.&#160; The licensing agreement with
the Company and US Airways for the LaGuardia commuter slots expired on December
31, 2006, but we maintain a security interest in the LaGuardia slots if US
Airways fails to perform under the current licensing agreement. The estimated
useful lives of these commuter slots&#160;were determined based upon the period
of time cash flows are expected to be generated by the commuter slots and by
researching the estimated useful lives of commuter slots or similar intangibles
by other airlines. In addition, an estimated residual value was determined using
estimates of the expected fair value of the commuter slots at the end of the
expected useful life. The residual value will be assessed annually for
impairment. The estimated useful lives are also reviewed
annually.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000;" face="Symbol, serif">&#183;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Reportable
Segments</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">.
The Company&#8217;s only reportable segment is scheduled transportation of passengers
and air freight under code-share agreements. In addition, the Company has
charter service, aircraft leasing and commuter slot licensing fee revenues.
These activities aggregated represent less than 10% of consolidated revenues,
operating income and assets. If these activities become more significant in
future years, additional reportable segments would need to be
disclosed.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Quarterly Information
(unaudited)</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The following table sets forth summary
quarterly financial information for the years ended December&#160;31, 2006 and
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2007</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div align="left">

                <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">Diluted</font></font></div>
              </td>
              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">43,277,470</font></font></td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>
              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">43,539,180</font></font></td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">43,948,625</font></font></td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

        </table>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">New Accounting
Standards</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">In July 2006, the Financial Accounting
Standards Board (FASB) issued FASB Interpretation No. 48, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting for
Uncertainty in Income Taxes&#8212;an Interpretation of FASB Statement No.&#160;109
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">(FIN&#160;48), which
clarifies the accounting for uncertainty in tax positions. This Interpretation
requires that we recognize in our financial statements, the impact of a tax
position, if that position is more likely than not of being sustained on audit,
based on the technical merits of the position. </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company adopted the provisions of
FIN 48 on January 1, 2007.&#160;&#160;The total amount of unrecognized tax
benefits as of the date of the adoption was $3.5 million</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;of which the Company had
previously recorded $1.2 million </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">for</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> income tax contingencies prior to the
adoption date.&#160;&#160;Accordingly, the Company recognized a $2.4 million
increase</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> in the liability
for the unrecognized tax benefits which was accounted for as a reduction to
retained earnings and an increase to deferred tax liability.&#160;&#160;During
the year ended December 31, 2007, the Company recognized approximately $0.9
million&#160;additional tax expense for unrecognized tax
benefits.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
September 2006, FASB issued SFAS No. 157, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; TEXT-DECORATION: none">Fair Value Measurements
</font>(SFAS 157). SFAS 157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for
measuring fair value, and expands disclosures about the use of fair value
measurements in accordance with generally accepted accounting
principles.&#160;&#160;SFAS 157 is effective for fiscal years beginning after
November 15, 2007. The Company has considered SFAS 157 and concluded that it
will not have a material impact on it consolidated financial
statements.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
February 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No. 159, <font style="TEXT-DECORATION: none"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic"><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; TEXT-DECORATION: none">The Fair Value Option for
Financial Assets and Financial Liab<font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; TEXT-DECORATION: none">i</font></font><font style="FONT-STYLE: italic; TEXT-DECORATION: none">lities</font>
</font></font>(SFAS 159). SFAS 159 is effective for fiscal years beginning after
November 15, 2007. SFAS 159 allows the Company to choose, at specified election
dates, to measure eligible financial assets and financial liabilities at fair
value that are not otherwise required to be measured at fair value. If a company
elects the fair value option for an eligible item, changes to that item's fair
value in subsequent reporting periods must be recognized in current earnings.
SFAS 159 also establishes presentation and disclosure requirements designed to
draw comparison between entities that elect different measurement attributes for
similar assets and liabilities.&#160;&#160;Upon review of the Company&#8217;s
financial assets and financial liabilities the Company has concluded there are
no eligible financial assets or financial liabilities applicable to SFAS
159.&#160;&#160;Subsequent to the effective date of SFAS 159, fiscal years
beginning after November 15, 2007, the Company will continue to review its
financial assets and financial liabilities and the applicability of SFAS
159.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
        <div id="FTR">
          <div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-47-</font></div>
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center">
            <hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="HDR">
          <div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
December 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No.&#160;141 (revised 2007), <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic">Business Combinations </font>(SFAS&#160;141R).
SFAS&#160;141R establishes principles and requirements for how an acquirer
recognizes and measures in its financial statements the identifiable assets
acquired, the liabilities assumed, any non-controlling interest in the acquiree
and the goodwill acquired. SFAS&#160;141R also establishes disclosure
requirements to enable the evaluation of the nature and financial effects of the
business combination. SFAS&#160;141R is effective for fiscal years beginning
after December&#160;15, 2008.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
December 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No.&#160;160, <font style="FONT-STYLE: italic">Non-controlling Interests in Consolidated Financial
Statements&#8212;an amendment of Accounting Research Bulletin No.&#160;51
</font>(SFAS&#160;160). SFAS&#160;160 establishes accounting and reporting
standards for ownership interests in subsidiaries held by parties other than the
parent, the amount of consolidated net income attributable to the parent and to
the non-controlling interest, changes in a parent's ownership interest, and the
valuation of retained non-controlling equity investments when a subsidiary is
deconsolidated. SFAS&#160;160 also establishes disclosure requirements that
clearly identify and distinguish between the interests of the parent and the
interests of the non-controlling owners. SFAS&#160;160 is effective for fiscal
years beginning after December&#160;15, 2008.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><a name="item7a"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">EM 7A. QUANT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ATIVE AND QUAL</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ATIVE DISCLOSURES ABOUT MARKET
RISK</font></a></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">We have been and are subject to market
risks, including commodity price risk (such as, to a limited extent, aircraft
fuel prices) and interest rate risk.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Interest Rates</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Our earnings can be affected by changes
in interest rates due to the amounts of variable rate debt and the amount of
cash and securities held. The interest rate applicable to variable rate debt may
rise and increase the amount of interest expense. At December 31, 2007 and
December 31, 2006 all of our long-term debt was fixed rate debt. We anticipate
that additional debt w</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">i</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ll be at fixed rates. However, we
believe we could fund any interest rate increases on additional variable rate
long-term debt with the increased amounts of interest
income.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">We currently intend to finance the
acquisition of aircraft through the manufacturer, third-party leases or
long-term borrowings. Changes in interest rates may impact the actual cost to us
to acquire these aircraft. To the extent we place these aircraft in service
under our code-share agreements our reimbursement rates may not be adjusted
higher or lower to reflect any changes in our aircraft rental
rates.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Beginning in April&#160;2004, in
anticipation of financing the purchase of regional jet aircraft on firm order
with the manufacturer, we entered into fourteen treasury lock agreements with
notional amounts totaling $373.5&#160;million and a weighted average interest
rate of 4.47% with expiration dates through June&#160;2005. Management
designated the treasury lock agreements as cash flow hedges of forecasted
transactions. The treasury lock agreements were settled at each respective
settlement date, which were the purchase dates of the respective aircraft. We
settled all of the agreements during 2004 and 2005 and the net amount paid was
$7.5&#160;million. Amounts paid or received on the settlement date are
reclassified to interest expense over the term of the respective aircraft debt.
During 2007 and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">6</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, we reclassified </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">0.8 million and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$0.3 million to interest expense,
respectively. The Company expects to reclassify </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$0.7 million to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> interest expense for the year ended
December 31, 2008.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div><br>

        <div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-49-</font></div>
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center">
            <hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="HDR">
          <div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">

      </div><br>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div>&#160;</div>
      <div align="center">
        <table bgcolor="white" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
            <tr>
              <td width="100%">
                <div align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><a name="report">REPORT OF INDEPENDENT REGISTERED PUBLIC ACCOUNTING FIRM
      </a></font></div>
              </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div>&#160;</div>
      <div align="center">
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">To the
Board of Directors and Stockholders of</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Republic
Airways Holdings Inc.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Indianapolis,
Indiana</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">We have
audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of Republic Airways
Holdings Inc. and subsidiaries (the &#8220;Company&#8221;) as of December&#160;31, 2007 and
2006, and the related consolidated statements of income, stockholders&#8217; equity
and comprehensive income, and cash flows for each of the three years in the
period ended December 31, 2007. We also have audited the Company&#8217;s internal
control over financial reporting as of December&#160;31, 2007, based on criteria
established in <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Internal
Control&#8212;Integrated Framework </font>issued by the Committee of Sponsoring
Organizations of the Treadway Commission. The Company&#8217;s management is
responsible for these consolidated financial statements, for maintaining
effective internal control over financial reporting, and for its assessment of
the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, included in the
accompanying Management&#8217;s Annual Report on Internal Control Over Financial
Reporting included in Item 9A.&#160;&#160;Our responsibility is to express an
opinion on these consolidated financial statements and an opinion on the
Company&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting based on our
audits.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">We
conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company
Accounting Oversight Board (United States). Those standards require that we plan
and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial
statements are free of material misstatement and whether effective internal
control over financial reporting was maintained in all material respects. Our
audits of the financial statements included examining, on a test basis, evidence
supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements, assessing
the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, and
evaluating the overall financial statement presentation. Our audit of internal
control over financial reporting included obtaining an understanding of internal
control over financial reporting, assessing the risk that a material weakness
exists, and testing and evaluating the design and operating effectiveness of
internal control based on the assessed risk. Our audits also included performing
such other procedures as we considered necessary in the
circumstances.&#160;&#160;We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis
for our opinions.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">A
company&#8217;s internal control over financial reporting is a process designed by, or
under the supervision of, the company&#8217;s principal executive and principal
financial officers, or persons performing similar functions, and effected by the
company&#8217;s board of directors, management, and other personnel to provide
reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the
preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with
generally accepted accounting principles. A company&#8217;s internal control over
financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that (1)&#160;pertain
to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly
reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the company;
(2)&#160;provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as
necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with
generally accepted accounting principles, and that receipts and expenditures of
the company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management
and directors of the company; and (3)&#160;provide reasonable assurance
regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use, or
disposition of the company&#8217;s assets that could have a material effect on the
financial statements.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">Because
of the inherent limitations of internal control over financial reporting,
including the possibility of collusion or improper management override of
controls, material misstatements due to error or fraud may not be prevented or
detected on a timely basis. Also, projections of any evaluation of the
effectiveness of the internal control over financial reporting to future periods
are subject to the risk that the controls may become inadequate because of
changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or
procedures may deteriorate.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In our
opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly,
in all material respects, the financial position of the Company as of
December&#160;31, 2007 and 2006, and the results of their operations and their
cash flows for each of the three years in the period ended December&#160;31,
2007, in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in the United
States of America. Also, in our opinion, the Company maintained, in all material
respects, effective internal control over financial reporting as of
December&#160;31, 2007, based on the criteria established in <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Internal Control&#8212;Integrated
Framework </font>issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the
Treadway Commission.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">As
discussed in Note 1 to the consolidated financial statements, substantially all
revenues are derived from code-share agreements with US Airways, Inc., Delta Air
Lines, Inc., AMR Corp., the parent of American Airlines, Inc., United Air Lines,
Inc., Continental Airlines, Inc., and Frontier Airlines, Inc.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">As
discussed in Note 2 to the consolidated financial statements, on January&#160;1,
2006, the Company adopted Statement of Financial Accounting Standards, No. 123
(Revised 2004), <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Share-Based
Payment</font>, using the modified prospective transition method.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">As
discussed in Note 11 to the consolidated financial statements, on January 1,
2007, the Company adopted the provisions of FASB Interpretation No. 48, <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting for Uncertainty in Income
Taxes &#8211; an Interpretation of FASB Statement No. 109</font>.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">/s/ DELO</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">TE &amp; TOUCHE LLP</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Indianapolis</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Indiana</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">February 19, 2008</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>

      </div><br>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"><a name="financialstatements">NOTES TO

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">FOR THE YEARS ENDED DECEMBER 31, 2007,
2006 and 2005</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">(Dollars in thousands, except share and
per share amounts)</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">1. ORGANIZATION&#160;&amp;
BUSINESS</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The accompanying consolidated financial
statements have been prepared in conformity with accounting principles generally
accepted in the United States of America and include the accounts of Republic
Airways Holdings Inc., a Delaware Corporation, and its wholly-owned operating
subsidiaries (collectively &#8220;Republic&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221;), Chautauqua Airlines,
Inc. (&#8220;Chautauqua&#8221;), an Indiana Corporation and certified air carrier; Shuttle
America Corporation (&#8220;Shuttle America&#8221;), an Indiana Corporation and certified
air carrier; and &#160;Republic Airline Inc. (&#8220;Republic Airline&#8221;) an Indiana
Corporation and certified air carrier.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Effective May 6, 2005, the Company
entered into a stock purchase agreement (the &#8220;Agreement&#8221;) with Shuttle
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">America and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> Shuttle Acquisition LLC (&#8220;Shuttle
LLC&#8221;), pursuant to which the Company acquired all of the issued and outstanding
common stock of Shuttle </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">America from</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> Shuttle LLC. Consideration paid was a
promissory note in the aggregate principal amount of $1,000 payable by Republic
to Shuttle LLC and the assumption of certain debt of Shuttle </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">America totaling</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> approximately $679. Because Republic
and Shuttle </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">America
were</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> commonly controlled by
Wexford Capital LLC (&#8220;Wexford&#8221;), the acquisition was accounted for in a manner
similar to a pooling of interests.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company operates as an air carrier
providing scheduled passenger and air freight service as US Airways Express,
AmericanConnection, Delta Connection</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">United Express</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, Continental Express and Frontier
Airlines under</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> code-share
agreements with US Airways,&#160;Inc. ("US Airways"), AMR Corporation
("American"), Delta Air Lines,&#160;Inc. ("Delta"), United Air Lines, Inc.
(&#8220;United&#8221;), </font>Continental Airlines, Inc. (&#8220;Continental&#8221;) and Frontier
Airlines, Inc. (&#8220;Frontier&#8221;),<font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
respectively.&#160;The Company&#160;has code-share agreements with US Airways
offering passenger and air freight service from US Airways' hub and focus
airports in Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, Indianapolis, Indiana,
Boston, Massachusetts, New York, New York (LaGuardia) and Washington, D.C. Under
the code-share agreement with American, the Company offers passenger and air
freight service from American's hub airport in </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">St. Louis</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Missouri</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The code-share agreements with Delta
offer passenger and air freight service from Delta's hub and focus airports in
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Atlanta</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Georgia</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Columbus</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Ohio</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Cincinnati</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Ohio</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. Under the code-share agreements with
United,&#160;the Company&#160;offers passenger and air freight service from
United&#8217;s hub airports in </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Chicago</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Illinois</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Washington</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">D.C.</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, (Dulles and National), the
Company&#160;offers passenger and air freight service from Continental&#8217;s hub in
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Houston</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Texas</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Cleveland</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Ohio</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> and the Company&#160;offers passenger
and air freight service from Frontier&#8217;s hub in </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Denver</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Colorado</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">US Airways Code</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-Share Agreement</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has code-share agreements
with US Airways to operate ERJ-145 and&#160;ERJ-170/175
aircraft.&#160;&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The
code-share agreement for the ERJ-145 aircraft terminates in March
2013.&#160;&#160;The code-share agreement for the ERJ-170 aircraft and the
ERJ-175 aircraft terminates in September 2015 with respect to the ERJ-170
aircraft and twelve years from the in-service date for each ERJ-175 aircraft. US
Airways may terminate the code-share agreements at any time for cause upon not
less than 90 days notice and subject to </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company&#8217;s right</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> to cure</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The American Code-Share
Agreement</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has a code-share agreement
with American to operate ERJ-140 aircraft.&#160;&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">If American terminates the code-share
agreement for cause, American has a call option to require that </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company assign</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> to American all of its rights under the
leases of aircraft, and to lease to American the aircraft to the extent
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company owns
them</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, used at that time
under the code-share agreement. If American exercises its call option,
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company is
required</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> to pay certain
maintenance costs in transferring the aircraft to American's maintenance
program.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">If American terminates the code-share
agreement without cause, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company has the</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> right to put the leases of the
aircraft, or to sell the aircraft to American to the extent owned by
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, used under the code-share agreement to
American. American also has a call option to require </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> assign to American these leases. If
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company
exercises</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">its put</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> or American exercises its call right,
both parties are obligated to implement a schedule to terminate the code-share
agreement in an orderly fashion and transition the aircraft from </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">to American.</font></font><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The term of the American code-share
agreement continues until February 1, 2013. American may reduce the term by one
year each time that the Company fails to achieve an agreed performance level.
American may only exercise this right three times during the term of the
code-share agreement. Under certain circumstances, the agreement may be subject
to termination for cause prior to that date.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Delta Code</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-Share Agreement</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The code-share agreements for the
ERJ-</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">135/</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">145 and ERJ-170 aircraft terminate in
May 2016 and January 2019, respectively. Delta may terminate the code-share
agreements at any time, with or without cause, if it provides </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company 180</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> days written notice, provided that such
notice shall not be given prior to November 2009 for the ERJ-145 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">regional jet </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">code-share agreement and July 2015 for
the ERJ-170 regional jet code-share agreement.&#160;&#160;If Delta does choose
to eliminate any aircraft at that time, it may not reduce the number of aircraft
in service to less than 12 during the 12-month period following the 180 day
initial notice period unless it completely terminates the code-share
agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">If Delta exercises this right under
either agreement or if </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the
Company terminates either</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
agreement for cause, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the
Company has the</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> right to
require Delta either to purchase, sublease or assume the lease of aircraft
leased by </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company
with</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">respect to any of the aircraft the
Company previously</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> operated
for Delta under that agreement. If </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company chooses not</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> to exercise this right, or if Delta
terminates either agreement for cause, Delta may require </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> sell or sublease to it or Delta may
assume the lease of aircraft leased by </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company with</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> respect to any of the aircraft
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company
previously</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> operated for it
under that agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">United </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Code-Share Agreement</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The ERJ-145 and ERJ-170 code-share
agreements terminate on June 30, 2014 and June 30, 2019, respectively. United
has the option of extending each agreement for five years or less; however, the
ERJ-145 code-share agreement may be terminated by United or </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">upon 18 months prior written notice
provided that such notice shall not be delivered by United prior to December 31,
2007, and&#160;&#160;by </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the
Company </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">prior to December
31, 2008. In addition, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">under certain conditions, United may
terminate </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the code-share
agreements</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">United has a call option to assume
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company&#8217;s
ownership</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> or leasehold
interest in certain aircraft if </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company wrongfully</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> terminates the</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> code-share agreements or if United
terminates the agreements for </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the Company&#8217;s breach</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> for certain
reasons.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Continental Code</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-Share Agreement</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The CRJ-200 aircraft are operated under
the code-share agreement on terms generally equivalent to the CRJ-200 leases,
which vary from two to five years.&#160;&#160;The ERJ-145 aircraft have a term
of three to five years.&#160;&#160;Under certain circumstances, Continental may
extend the term on the aircraft up to five additional
years.&#160;&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The term
of the agreement is effective as of January 8, 2007 and, unless earlier
terminated or extended, will continue until July, 2012.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Frontier Code</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-Share Agreement</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">On January 11, 2007, we entered into an
air services agreement with Frontier. Under the agreement, we will provide and
operate </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">17 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">RJ-170 aircraft for</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> Frontier.&#160;&#160;The first aircraft
was placed into service in March 2007 and the last aircraft is expected to be
placed into service </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">in
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">December 2008. The
agreement has a term of eleven years from the date of the last aircraft
delivery. Frontier has the option to extend the agreement for up to six
additional years. The term of the agreement became effective as of March 2007,
and, unless earlier terminated or extended, will continue until December
2019.</font></font></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">For the years ended December 31, 2007,
2006 and 2005, substantially all of the Company's revenue is derived from
agreements with its Partners. Termination of any of these code-share agreements
could have a material adverse effect on the Company's financial position,
results of operations and cash flows.</font></font></div>
