      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2. SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING
POLICIES</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Basis
of Consolidation</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;The
consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company and its
wholly-owned subsidiaries, Chautauqua, Shuttle </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">America and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> Republic Airline. All significant
intercompany accounts and transactions are eliminated in
consolidation.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Risk
Management</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;The Company
accounts for derivatives in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting
Standard (SFAS) No.&#160;133, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting for
Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">as amended and interpreted</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Beginning in April&#160;2004, in
anticipation of financing the purchase of regional jet aircraft on firm order
with the manufacturer, the Company entered into fourteen treasury lock
agreements with notional amounts totaling $373,500&#160;and a weighted average
interest rate of 4.47% with expiration dates through June&#160;2005. Management
designated the treasury lock agreements as cash flow hedges of forecasted
transactions. The treasury lock agreements were settled at each respective
settlement date, which were the purchase dates of the respective aircraft. The
Company settled all of the agreements during 2004 and 2005 and the net amount
paid was $7,472, and was recorded in accumulated other comprehensive loss, net
of tax. Amounts paid or received on the settlement date are reclassified to
interest expense over the term of the respective aircraft debt. During
200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">7</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, 2006 and 200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">5</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, the Company reclassified $</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">761, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$299 and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">286 to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> interest expense, respectively. The
Company expects to reclassify </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$720 to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> interest expense for the year ending
December 31, 2008.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Cash
and Cash Equivalents</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;Cash
equivalents consist of money market funds and short-term, highly liquid
investments with maturities of three months or less when purchased.
Substantially all of our cash is on hand with </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">two </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">bank</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;Supplemental Cash Flow
Information:</font></font></div>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>
              <td align="left" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>
              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;</font></font></td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;</font></font></td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="9%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">4,012</font></font></td>

              <td align="left" valign="bottom" width="64%">
                <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Excess tax benefit for stock
      options exercised</font></font></div>
              </td>
              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              <td align="left" valign="bottom" width="64%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">Fair

              <td align="right" valign="bottom" width="1%"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

        </table>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Inventories
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">consist primarily of spare
parts and supplies, which are charged to expense as they are used in operations.
Inventories are valued at average cost. An allowance for obsolescence is
provided to reduce inventory to estimated net realizable value. As of December
31, 2007 and 2006 this reserve was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$2,157 and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> $1,004,
respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Aircraft
and Other Equipment </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">is
carried at cost. Incentives received from the aircraft manufacturer are recorded
as reductions to the cost of the aircraft. Depreciation for aircraft is computed
on a straight-line basis to an estimated salvage value over 16.5&#160;years, the
estimated useful life of the regional jet aircraft. Depreciation for other
equipment, including rotable parts, is computed on a straight-line basis over 3
to 10&#160;years, the estimated useful lives of the other equipment. Leasehold
improvements are amortized over the expected life or lease term, whichever is
less. Interest related to deposits on aircraft on firm order from the
manufacturer is capitalized. The Company capitalized approximately </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$4,056, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$2,021 and $1,904 of interest for the
years ended December&#160;31, 2007, 2006 and 2005,
respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">
        <div id="FTR">
          <div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
          </div>

        <div id="PN" style="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: always">
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-57-</font></div>
          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center">
            <hr style="COLOR: black" noshade size="2">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div id="HDR">
          <div id="GLHDR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="right">
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Restricted
Cash </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">consists of restricted
amounts for satisfying debt and lease payments due within the next twelve month
period.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Debt
Issue Costs </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">are capitalized
and included in intangible and other assets and are amortized, using the
effective interest method, to interest expense over the term of the related
debt. Debt issue costs, net of accumulated amortization, of </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$22,27</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">1 and $17,560 are included in intangible
and other assets in the consolidated balance sheets as of December&#160;31, 2007
and 2006, respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Goodwill</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">and
Intangible Assets are</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
accounted for in accordance with SFAS No. 142, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Goodwill and Other
Intangible Assets</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. Goodwill
and intangible assets that have indefinite useful lives are not amortized but
are tested at least annually for impairment. Management reviewed the carrying
value of goodwill and concluded that no asset impairment existed as of December
31, 200</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">7</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. Intangible assets that have finite
useful lives are amortized over their useful lives to an estimated residual
value and reviewed for impairment at each reporting date. At December 31, 2007
the remaining amortization period for the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Ronald</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Reagan</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Washington</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">National</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Airport commuter</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> slots is 23</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> years. Estimated amortization expense
will approximate $388 per year.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Long-Lived
Assets</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;Management reviews
long-lived assets for possible impairment, if there is a significant event that
detrimentally affects operations. The primary financial indicator used by the
Company to assess the recoverability of its long-lived assets held and used is
undiscounted future cash flows from operations. The amount of impairment if any,
is measured based on estimated fair value or projected future cash flows using a
discount rate reflecting the Company's average cost of funds. </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">M</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">anagement has concluded that no asset
impairment existed as of December 31, 2007.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Deferred
Credits </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">consist of credits
for parts and training from the aircraft and engine manufacturers</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">deferred gains from the sale and
leaseback of aircraft and spare jet engines and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> deferred revenue from the Delta warrant
surrender and pre-petition claim</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. Deferred credits are amortized on a
straight-line basis as a reduction of aircraft or engine rent expense over the
term of the respective leases</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.&#160;&#160;The deferred revenue is
amortized as an adjustment to regional airline services revenue based on the
weighted average aircraft in service over the life of the Delta
agreements.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Comprehensive
Income&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company reports
comprehensive income in accordance with SFAS No.&#160;130, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Reporting
Comprehensive Income, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">which
establishes standards for reporting and displaying comprehensive income and its
components in financial statements. The Company had accumulated other
comprehensive loss relating to treasury lock agreements of </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$3,009, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$3,877 and $4,176, net of tax, at
December 31, 2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Income
Taxes</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company accounts for income taxes
using the asset and liability method. Under the asset and liability method,
deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the future tax
consequences attributable to differences between the financial statement
carrying amounts for existing assets and liabilities and their respective tax
bases. Deferred tax assets and liabilities are measured using enacted tax rates
expected to apply to taxable income in future years in which those temporary
differences are expected to be recovered or settled. The measurement of deferred
tax assets is adjusted by a valuation allowance, if necessary, to recognize the
future tax benefits to the extent, based on available evidence; it is more
likely than not they will be realized.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;Aircraft
Maintenance and Repair </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">is
charged to expense as incurred under the direct expense method. Engines and
certain airframe component overhaul and repair costs are subject to
power-by-the-hour contracts with external vendors and are expensed as the
aircraft are flown.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Use
of Estimates&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The
preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles
generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make
estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and
liabilities and disclosure of contingent assets and liabilities at the date of
the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenues and expenses
during the reporting periods. Under the code-share agreements, the Company
estimates operating costs for certain &#8220;pass through&#8221; costs and records revenue
based on these estimates. Actual results could differ from those
estimates.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Revenue
Recognition&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Regional
airline service revenues, charter revenues and ground handling revenues are
recognized in the period the services are provided.&#160; Under our fixed-fee
arrangements with American, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Delta</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">US </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Airways, United, Continental and
Frontier, the Company receives fixed-fee</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, as well as reimbursement of specified
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8220;pass-through&#8221; </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">costs on a gross basis with additional
possible incentives from our Partners for superior service. Regional airline
service revenues are recognized in the period the service is </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">provided and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> we perform an estimate of the profit
component based upon the information available at the end of the accounting
period.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The reimbursement of specified costs,
known as &#8220;pass-through costs&#8221;, may include aircraft ownership cost, passenger
liability and hull insurance, aircraft property taxes, fuel, landing fees and
catering. All revenue recognized under these contracts is presented at the gross
amount billed for reimbursement pursuant to Emerging Issues Tax Force Issue
(&#8220;E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">F&#8221;) No. 99-19&#160; </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Reporting Revenue
Gross as a Principal versus Net as an Agent</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Under the Company&#8217;s code-share
agreements, the Company is reimbursed an amount per aircraft designed to
compensate the Company for certain aircraft ownership costs. In accordance with
E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">F No.&#160;01-08, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Determining Whether
an Arrangement Contains a Lease</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, the Company has concluded that a
component of its revenue under the agreement discussed above is rental income,
inasmuch as the agreement identifies the &#8220;right of use&#8221; of a specific type and
number of aircraft over a stated period of time. The amount deemed to be rental
income during fiscal 2007, 2006 and 2005 was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$310,250</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $258,600 and $189,800, respectively,
and has been included in regional airline services revenue on the Company&#8217;s
consolidated statements of income.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">

          <div style="WIDTH: 100%; TEXT-ALIGN: center"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">-58-</font></div>

      </div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company recognizes lease revenue for
subleases of </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">six
ERJ</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-145 aircraft subleased
to an airline in </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Mexico
under</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> operating leases
which expire in 2013 and 2015. In addition, the Company recognizes license
revenue from US Airways for commuter slots that were purchased by the Company in
2005 and were utilized by US Airways through 2006 for the New-York LaGuardia
commuter slots, and through 2016 for the Ronald Reagan Washington National
commuter slots. Revenues from subleases and the commuter slots are recognized
when earned and included in other operating revenue.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company records any tax assessed by
a governmental authority that is directly imposed on a revenue-producing
transaction between the Company and its customers on a net
basis.&#160;&#160;These taxes are currently not material to the Company&#8217;s
consolidated financial statements.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Warrants&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Warrants issued to non-employees and
Partners are accounted for under SFAS No. 123(R), </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Share-Based
Payment</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">and E</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">F 96-18, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting for
Equity Instruments That Are Issued to Other Than Employees for Acquiring, or in
Conjunction with Selling, Goods or Services,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">at fair value on the measurement date as
deferred charges and credits to stockholders&#8217; equity. Warrants surrendered in a
non-monetary transaction are recorded at fair value on the measurement date as
reductions to deferred warrant charges and stockholders&#8217; equity. The deferred
charges for warrants </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">were
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">amortized as a reduction of
regional airline services revenue over the terms of the code-share agreements.
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;&#160;In March 2007,
the Company amended its agreements with Delta and&#160;&#160;in return for these
amended terms, Delta agreed to surrender its warrants for 3,435,000 shares of
the Company&#8217;s common stock, and the Company was granted a pre-petitioned,
unsecured, general claim in the amount of $91,000 in Delta's Chapter 11
bankruptcy case. In April 2007, the Company sold the $91,000 pre-petition claim
to a third party for $44,590 in cash.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt; TEXT-ALIGN: justify" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000">As a result of the
Delta amendment, in March 2007, the Company recorded a deferred credit of
$44,590, which represented the net realizable value of the pre-petition claim on
the approval date by the Bankruptcy Court. In addition, the Company recorded a
deferred gain on the surrender of the warrants from Delta of $42,735, which was
net of the write-off of the previously reported unamortized deferred warrant
charge of $6,369. Stockholders' equity was reduced by $32,892, net of tax,
resulting from the surrender of the warrants and their retirement. The deferred
credits for the proceeds of the pre-petition claim and the gain on the surrender
of the warrants totaling $87,325 will be amortized as an adjustment to revenue
over&#160;the weighted average aircraft in service during the term of the
agreements with Delta. </font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Stock
Compensation&#8212;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company
maintains stock-based compensation plans which allow for the issuance of
nonqualified stock options to officers, other key employees of the Company, and
to members of the Board of Directors. Prior to 2006, the Company accounted for
the stock option plans under the provisions of Accounting Principles Board
Opinion No. 25, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Accounting for Stock
Issued to Employees</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, and
related Interpretations, whereby,&#160;stock options granted that had an
exercise price below the market value were recorded as stock compensation
expense. Effective January 1, 2006, the Company adopted the fair value
recognition provisions of SFAS No. 123(R), </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Share-Based Payment
(</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">SFAS&#160;123R). This
statement applies to all awards granted after the effective date and to
modifications, repurchases or cancellations of existing awards. Additionally,
under the modified prospective method of adoption, the Company recognizes
compensation expense for the portion of outstanding awards on the adoption date
for which the requisite service period has not yet been rendered based on the
grant-date fair value of those awards calculated under SFAS&#160;123R.
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The standard also requires
that forfeitures be estimated over the vesting period of an award, rather than
being recognized as a reduction of compensation expense when the forfeiture
actually occurs.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br>&#160;</div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">

Income per Common Share </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">is
based on the weighted average number of shares outstanding during the
period.</font></font></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Employee stock options of </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">1,366,000 were</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> not included in the calculation of
diluted net income per common share due to their anti-dilutive impact for the
year ended December&#160;31, 2007. For the years ended December 31, 2006 and
2005, all of the employee stock options and warrants were included in the
calculation of the dilutive net income per common share.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Segment
Information</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;The Company has
one reportable operating segment for the scheduled transportation of passengers
and air freight under code-share agreements. The Company&#8217;s charter service, slot
leasing and aircraft leasing revenues are not considered
material.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">New
Accounting Standards</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8212;In
September 2006, the </font>Financial Accounting Standards Board "FASB"<font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> issued SFAS No. 157, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Fair Value
Measurements <font style="FONT-STYLE: normal">(<font style="FONT-STYLE: normal">SFAS 157</font>)</font></font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, which defines fair value, establishes
a framework for measuring fair value and requires expanded disclosures about
fair value measurements. This statement is effective for fiscal years beginning
after November 15, 2007. The Company </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">will apply the provisions of
SFAS&#160;157, as necessary.&#160;&#160;The adoption did not have a material
effect on our statement of financial position or results of
operations.&#160;&#160;</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
February 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No. 159, <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">The Fair Value Option for Financial
Assets and Financial Liabilities</font> (SFAS&#160;159). SFAS&#160;159 is
effective for fiscal years beginning after November 15, 2007. SFAS&#160;159
allows the Company to choose, at specified election dates, to measure eligible
financial assets and financial liabilities at fair value that are not otherwise
required to be measured at fair value. If a company elects the fair value option
for an eligible item, changes to that item's fair value in subsequent reporting
periods must be recognized in current earnings. SFAS&#160;159 also establishes
presentation and disclosure requirements designed to draw comparison between
entities that elect different measurement attributes for similar assets and
liabilities.&#160;&#160;The Company did not elect to fair value any of its
financial assets or financial liabilities, therefore, the adoption of
SFAS&#160;159 did not have a material effect on the Company&#8217;s consolidated
financial statements.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
December 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No.&#160;141 (revised 2007), <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Business Combinations
</font>(SFAS&#160;141R). SFAS&#160;141R establishes principles and requirements
for how an acquirer recognizes and measures in its financial statements the
identifiable assets acquired, the liabilities assumed, any non-controlling
interest in the acquiree and the goodwill acquired. SFAS&#160;141R also
establishes disclosure requirements to enable the evaluation of the nature and
financial effects of the business combination. SFAS&#160;141R is effective for
fiscal years beginning after December&#160;15, 2008.&#160;&#160;The Company has
not yet completed its assessment of the impact of this statement on its
consolidated financial statements.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div id="PGBRK" style="MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt">

          <div id="GLFTR" style="WIDTH: 100%" align="left">
          </div>
        </div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In
December 2007, the FASB issued SFAS No.&#160;160, <font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-STYLE: italic">Non-controlling Interests in
Consolidated Financial Statements&#8212;an amendment of Accounting Research Bulletin
No.&#160;51</font> (SFAS&#160;160). SFAS&#160;160 establishes accounting and
reporting standards for ownership interests in subsidiaries held by parties
other than the parent, the amount of consolidated net income attributable to the
parent and to the non-controlling interest, changes in a parent's ownership
interest, and the valuation of retained non-controlling equity investments when
a subsidiary is deconsolidated. SFAS&#160;160 also establishes disclosure
requirements that clearly identify and distinguish between the interests of the
parent and the interests of the non-controlling owners. SFAS&#160;160 is
effective for fiscal years beginning after December&#160;15, 2008. The Company
has not yet completed its assessment of the impact of this statement on its
consolidated financial statements.</font></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company purchased commuter slots at
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Ronald</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Reagan</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Washington</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">National</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Airport </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">(&#8220;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">DCA</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#8221;) and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">New York</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">LaGuardia</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Airport
 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">(&#8220;LGA&#8221;) in 2005 from US Airways. The
licensing agreement with the Company and US Airways for the LGA commuter slots
expired on December 31, 2006, but we maintain a security interest in the LGA
slots if US Airways fails to perform under the current licensing agreement. The
LGA commuter slots were amortized over a 15 month life ending December 31, 2006,
and the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">DCA
commuter</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> slots are
amortized on a straight line basis over a 25 year expected life to an estimated
residual value. Amortization was approximately $3,671 in 2006 and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$388 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">in 2007. The Company assigned the right
of use for these commuter slots to US Airways which will continue to be operated
by US Airways Express carriers until the expiration or termination of the
amended and restated Chautauqua Jet Service Agreement (&#8220;JSA&#8221;) dated as of April
26, 2005 between US Airways and Chautauqua or the Republic JSA, whichever is
later, at an agreed rate. Prior to the expiration of the agreement to license
the commuter slots, US Airways has the right to repurchase all, but not less
than all, of the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">DCA
commuter</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> slots at a
predetermined price.</font></font></div>

              <td align="left" valign="bottom" width="76%" style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify">
                <div style="TEXT-ALIGN: justify"><font style="FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">Revolving credit
      facility with Bank of America Business Capital (the &#8220;Bank&#8221;), maximum of
      $15,000 available (including outstanding letters of credit), subject to
      30% of the net book value of spare rotable parts and 15% of the net
      book&#160;value of spare non-rotable parts and inventory. Interest is
      payable monthly at the bank&#8217;s LIBOR rate plus spreads ranging from 2.50%
      to 2.75% or the Bank&#8217;s base rate (which is generally equivalent to the
      prime rate) plus spreads ranging from 0.50% to 0.75%. Fees are payable at
      0.375% on the unused revolver amount. The credit facility expires on March
      31, 2009 and is collateralized by all the Company&#8217;s assets, excluding the
      owned aircraft and engines.</font></div>

</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">with Bank of America
Business Capital </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">has
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">a liquidity
covenant</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">a </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">specified fixed charge coverage ratio
and a debt to earnings leverage ratio covenant. </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company was in compliance with the
covenant</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">at December 31,
2007.&#160;&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The credit
facility limits the Company&#8217;s ability to incur indebtedness or create or incur
liens on its assets.</font></font></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">During the year ended December 31, 2007,
the Company acquired </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">22
aircraft through debt financing totaling approximately $438,252</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The debt was obtained from banks and
the aircraft manufacturer for twelve to fifteen year terms at interest rates
ranging from </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">6.22% to
7.28%</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">7. COMM</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">MENTS</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">As of December 31, 2007, the Company
leased </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">91 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aircraft and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">22 spare</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> regional jet engines with varying terms
extending through </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2029 and
terminal space, operating facilities and office equipment with terms extending
through 2026 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">under
operating leases. The components of rent expense for the years ended
December&#160;31 are as follows:</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements with an avionics equipment manufacturer and maintenance provider that
has a guaranteed minimum annual flight hour requirement. The minimum guaranteed
amount based on the Company's current operations is </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$4,852 per</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> year through December&#160;2014 for the
ERJ-145 family of aircraft and </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$8,161 per</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> year through December 2014 for the
ERJ-170 family of aircraft. The Company did not record a liability for this
guarantee because the Company does not believe that any aircraft will be
utilized below the minimum flight hour requirement during the term of the
agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements with </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aviation
equipment manufacturers </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">for
the ERJ-145 family of aircraft and the CRJ-200 aircraft through </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">June</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2013 and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> December 2012, respectively. The
agreement has a penalty payment provision if more than twenty percent of the
Company's aircraft are removed from service based on the annual flight activity
prior to the date of removal. The Company did not record a liability for this
penalty provision because the Company does not believe that more than twenty
percent of their aircraft will be removed from service during the term of the
agreement.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements based upon </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">flight activity with engine
manufacturers </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">through
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">February 2010 for the
CRJ-200 aircraft, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">October
2012 for the ERJ-145 family of aircraft and through December 2014 for the
ERJ-170 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">family of
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aircraft.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has long-term maintenance
agreements for </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">wheels and
brakes through</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">
June&#160;2014 for the ERJ-145 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">family of </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aircraft and through 2017 for the
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ERJ-170 family of
aircraft</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The agreement has
an early termination penalty, if the Company removes sellers equipment from
certain aircraft, sells or leases certain aircraft to a third party or
terminates the services prior to expiration of the agreement. The Company did
not record a liability for this penalty provision, because the Company does not
believe the contract will be terminated prior to the expiration
date.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company has a long-term agreement to
provide, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">manage and repair
certain airframe components and spare parts on</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> the CRJ-200 aircraft through December
2009.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Total payments under these long-term
maintenance agreements were </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$76,832</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $56,070 and $53,647 for the years
ended December&#160;31, 2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">As part of the Company's lease
agreements, the Company typically indemnifies the lessor of the respective
aircraft against liabilities that may arise due to changes in benefits from tax
ownership or tax laws of the respective leased aircraft. The Company has not
recorded a liability for these indemnifications because they are not estimable.
The Company is responsible for all other maintenance costs of its aircraft and
must meet specified return conditions upon lease expiration for both the air
frames and engines. The Company is unable to estimate the liability for these
return conditions as of December 31, 2007, because the leases expire beginning
in 2009. The Company will record a liability for these return conditions once
the liability is probable and reasonably estimable.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>

non-cancelable operating leases are as follows for the years ending

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">As of December 31, 2007, the Company had
firm orders to purchase </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">29
ERJ</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">-170/175 aircraft all of
which are currently allocated to code-share agreements. The current total list
price of the 29 aircraft is $</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">899,000</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The Company has received commitments
from</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> third parties
to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> finance all</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> of these aircraft. During the year
ended December 31, 2007, the Company </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">paid</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">aircraft deposits totaling</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> $51,414 in</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> accordance with the aircraft
commitments</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. Aircraft
deposits are included in intangible and other assets. The Company also has a
commitment to acquire </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">nine
spare</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> aircraft engines with
a current list price of approximately </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$40,500</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. These commitments are subject to
customary closing conditions.</font></font></div>

with an aircraft manufacturer are shown below as of December 31,

              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2px"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>
              <td valign="bottom" style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2px"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

              </td>
              <td align="left" nowrap valign="bottom" style="PADDING-BOTTOM: 2px"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: times new roman">&#160;</font></td>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">8. CONTINGENCIES</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company is subject to certain legal
and administrative actions which management considers routine to their business
activities. As of December 31, 2007, management believes, after consultation
with legal counsel, the ultimate outcome of any pending legal matters will not
have a material adverse effect on the Company's financial position, liquidity or
results of operations.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">American may terminate the code-share
agreement without cause upon 180&#160;days notice, provided that such notice may
not be given prior to September&#160;30, 2008. If American exercises this right,
it is required to reimburse us for certain costs and the Company and American
have certain "put" and "call" rights with respect to the aircraft we operate for
them.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">If Delta exercises its partial
termination right or if we terminate the code-share agreement because of Delta's
bankruptcy or insolvency, a breach of the agreement by Delta or because of an
event of force majeure has occurred that continues for at least two consecutive
months, we may require Delta to either purchase or sublease any of the
terminated aircraft we own at a specified price or to assume the lease of any
aircraft that we lease. If we choose not to exercise this "put" right upon any
termination by Delta, Delta has the right to require us to sell or sublease to
them the terminated aircraft we own for a specified amount or to assume the
leases of the terminated aircraft that we lease. Delta may also exercise this
"call" right if it terminates the code-share agreement for any of the reasons
set forth above.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">United has a call option to assume our
ownership or leasehold interest in certain aircraft if we wrongfully terminate
the code-share agreements or if United terminates the agreements for our breach
of certain reasons.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">As of December 31, 2007, approximately
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">77% </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">of the Company's workforce is employed
under union contracts. Th</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">e
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">union contract for
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Pilots is currently
amendable.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt">&#160;</div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; COLOR: #000000">9. RELATED PARTY
TRANSACTIONS</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">WexAir RJET LLC, which is owned by
several investment funds managed by Wexford, previously held a majority interest
in our common stock. Currently, Wexford owns less than </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">1</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">% of our common stock but</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> o</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ne of our directors is a general partner
of Wexford and its affiliates.</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Wexford and its affiliates are actively
engaged in the airline business. Conflicts of interest may in the future arise
between Wexford and its affiliates, on the one hand, and us, on the other hand,
in a number of areas relating to our business and our past and ongoing
relationships.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Fees are paid to Wexford for
administrative functions not performed by the Company. Fees incurred were
approximately&#160;$324 and $1,065 for the years ended December&#160;31, 2006
and 2005, respectively. In addition, included in accrued liabilities were
$26&#160;due to Wexford Capital as of December&#160;31,
2006.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">During 2007, the Company purchased from
WexAir RJET LLC a total&#160;&#160;of 6,555,000 shares of its holdings in the
Company&#8217;s common stock, par value $.001 per share, at a weighted average price
of $20.15 per share, for total consideration
of&#160;&#160;$132,100.&#160;&#160;The transactions were recorded as treasury
stock on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance sheet.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-WEIGHT: bold; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">10. C</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">AP</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">IT</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">AL STOCK, STOCK OPTIONS AND
WARRANTS</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">In March
2007, the Company purchased from WexAir RJET LLC 2,000,000 shares of its
holdings in the Company&#8217;s common stock, par value $.001 per share, at a price of
$20.50 per share, for total consideration of $41,000. The transaction was
recorded as treasury stock on the Company&#8217;s consolidated balance
sheet.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="left"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="BACKGROUND-COLOR: white"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; BACKGROUND-COLOR: white">On August 28, 2007, the
Company&#8217;s Board of Directors authorized the purchase of up to $100,000 of the
Company&#8217;s common stock.&#160;&#160;The buy-back program provided for the shares
to be purchased on the open market or through privately-negotiated transactions
from time-to-time during the twelve month period following the
authorization.&#160;&#160;Under the authorization, the timing and amount of
purchase would be based upon market conditions, securities law limitations and
other factors.&#160;&#160;The stock buy-back program did not obligate the
Company to acquire any specific number of shares in any period, and could be
modified, suspended, extended or discontinued at any time without prior notice.
The Company purchased 4,994,159 shares of which 4,555,000 were purchased from
WexAir LLC and the remainder were purchased on the open market at a weighted
average stock price of $20.02 for total consideration of $100,000. This
authorization was closed in November 2007.</font></font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman">On
December 14, 2007, the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors authorized the purchase of
up to $100,000 of the Company&#8217;s common stock.&#160;&#160; The shares will be
purchased on the open market or through privately-negotiated transactions from
time-to-time during the twelve month period following the authorization. Under
the authorization, the timing and amount of purchase would be based upon market
conditions, securities law limitations and other factors. The stock buy-back
program does not obligate the Company to acquire any specific number of shares
in any period, and may be modified, suspended, extended or discontinued at any
time without prior notice. As of December 31, 2007, pursuant to this
authorization, the Company purchased 72,735 shares on the open market at a
weighted average stock price of $19.42 for total consideration of $1,412. At
December 31, 2007, the amount under this authorization was $98,588.</font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">At December 31, 2007, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">2,710,818 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">shares of the Company&#8217;s 150,000,000
authorized shares were reserved for issuances under the Equity Incentive Plans.
At December 31, 2007, the number of securities remaining available for future
issuance under equity compensation plans was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">3,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">728,</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">000 shares</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.&#160;</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Employee Stock
Options</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The 2002 Equity Incentive Plan provides
for the granting of up to 2,180,000 shares of our common stock and as of
December 31, 2007, 47,215 shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock remain available
for issuance under the plan.&#160;&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The 2007 Equity Incentive Plan provides
for the granting of up to </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">5,000,000 shares</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> of our common stock and</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> as of December 31, 2007, 3,680,000
shares of the Company&#8217;s common stock remain available for issuance under the
plan.</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">S</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">tock options </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">granted under these plans typically
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">vest ratably over
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">the term of the employment
agreements or </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">48 months and
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">are granted</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> with exercise prices equal to market
prices on the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">date of
grant</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">. The options normally
expire</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> ten years from the
date of grant. </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Options are </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">typically </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">granted to officers and key employees
selected by the Compensation Committee of the Board of
Directors.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">In connection with employment agreements
for certain key employees,&#160;the Company&#160;granted options to purchase
shares of the Company's common stock with exercise prices ranging from
$</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">7.83 to</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$2</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">0.27</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.&#160;These stock options vest ratably
over the term of the employment agreements or</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> 48 months</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">a</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">nd are exercisable for five years
following the vesting dates or</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> ten years from the date of
grant</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000; FONT-STYLE: italic">Non-employee
Director Stock Options</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">&#160;</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The Company also granted options for
non-employee directors </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">on
the day prior to commencement of the Company&#8217;s initial public offering
</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">under the 2002 Equity
Incentive Plan at a price equal to the fair market value of the </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">c</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">ommon </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">s</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">tock on the date of the grant. These
Options</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> vested
over</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> a 3 year period with
1/24 of the shares vesting monthly for the first 12 months and 1/48 of the
shares vesting monthly over the remaining 24 months. </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">Additionally, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">non-employee directors are to receive
2,500 options on the first trading day after each annual meeting of stockholders
at which he or she is re-elected as a non-employee director. These options vest
ratably over 12 months of continuous service. The non-employee options are
exercisable until 10 years from the date of grant.&#160;</font></font></div>

      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="center">&#160;</div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The intrinsic value of options exercised
during the years ended December 31, 2007, 2006 and 2005 was $</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">6,081</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $12,429 and
$5,140.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; COLOR: #000000; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">There were 1,199,052 and 1,709,700
options exercisable at December 31, 2006 and 2005 respectively. The weighted
average exercise price for the options exercisable at December 31, 2006 and 2005
was $11.92 and $4.07. The remaining contractual life for the options outstanding
at December 31, 2006 and 2005 was 7.6 years and 6.3 years,
respectively.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">During the years ended December 31,
2007, 2006 and 2005, </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$3,119
($1,871 net of tax)</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $1,297
($785 net of tax) and $125 ($75 net of tax), respectively, was charged to
expense relating to the stock option plans. The Company has a policy of issuing
new common shares to satisfy the exercise of stock options. At December 31, 2007
there was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$7,808
of</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000"> unrecognized stock-based
employee compensation expense for unvested stock options, and the expected
remaining expense period is </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">3.9 </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">years. The Company did not recognize
excess tax benefits related to stock option exercises in 2007 since the Company
did not have taxable income in 2007.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; MARGIN-LEFT: 0pt; TEXT-INDENT: 36pt; MARGIN-RIGHT: 0pt" align="justify"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; FONT-SIZE: 10pt; FONT-FAMILY: Times New Roman"><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">The weighted average grant date fair
value of options granted in 2007, 2006 and 2005 was </font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">$5.30</font><font style="DISPLAY: inline; COLOR: #000000">, $7.62, and $3.98, respectively. The
Company estimates the fair value of stock options issued using the Black-Scholes
option pricing model. Expected volatilities are based on the historical
volatility of the Company&#8217;s stock and other factors. The Company uses historical
data to estimate option exercises and employee terminations within the valuation
model. Dividends were based on an estimated dividend yield. The risk-free rates
for the periods within the contractual life of the option are based on the U.S.
Treasury rates in effect at the time of the grant. The forfeiture rate is based
on historical information and managements best estimate of future forfeitures.
The expected term of options granted is derived from historical exercise
experience and represents the period of time the Company expects options granted
to be outstanding. Option valuation models require the input of subjective
assumptions including the expected volatility and lives. Actual values of grants
could vary significantly from the results of the
calculations.</font></font></div>
      <div style="DISPLAY: block; TEXT-INDENT: 0pt"><br></div>

value stock option grants during the following periods:</font></font></div>
